data.notes: Available during accumulation phase. Upon death of annuitant, benefit will be equal to - 1) contract value, 2) adjusted purchase payments or 3) Enhanced Death Benefit Base. Enhanced death benefit base is equal to initial purchase payment at rider issue. After rider effective date, Enhanced death benefit base will be equal to highest contract value at any contract anniversary following annuitant's 80th birthday. Withdrawal will adjusted the benefit base to greater of - 1) dollar amount of withdrawal or 2) amount of withdrawal multiplied by ratio of contract value before the withdrawal. Contract value will be immediately credited with purchase payment enhancement for every purchase payment. Issuer also provides a feature Enhancement True-Up, which will increase enhanced death benefit base in the event that poor market performance does not result in a step-up, or if stepped-up value does not include the full amount of the purchase payment enhancement. There is a three-year waiting period for inclusion of purchase payment enhancements in the enhanced death benefit base. The enhancement true-ups will cease once a withdrawal is taken. At the time of enhanced death benefit base enhancement true-up evaluation, enhanced death benefit base will be compared to enhanced death benefit true-up base. The enhanced death benefit true-up base is the sum of - 1) purchase payments, up to, but not including the date on which the evaluation takes place, and 2) purchase payment enhancements which are at least 36 months old as of the date of the evaluation. If a step-up takes place, any purchase payment enhancements which are part of the contract value also become part of the enhanced death benefit base. Benefit base can never be more than $1,000,000. Current Charges are 0.20% if purchased in combination.

data.notes: Benefit guarantees minimum level of future income regardless of investment performance of underlying investment options. Benefit base initially is equal to contract value on the rider effective date, increased by purchase payments made during first contract year. If the benefit base exceeds contract value at the end of benefit period, company will increase the contract value so that it equals benefit base. At the end of the benefit period, the contract owner can elect to receive the benefit or renew the rider for a new benefit period. Benefit period duration is 10 years. Step-Up benefit is the increase of benefit to an amount equal to 100% of contract value as of the Step-Up benefit date. Owner may lock-in the investment gains by electing to increase the benefit base through the use of the step-up.

data.notes: Benefit guarantees minimum Contract Value at the end of the Benefit Period. Owner may elect 7 (100%) years benefit period either at the time of contract issuance or later during any subsequent contract anniversary. Effective from July 1, 2023, 5-year Accumulation benefit is no longer available for new purchases; notwithstanding the foregoing, the same accumulation benefit will remain available for previous purchases only if owner/annuitant select a reset their benefit either into 7-year accumulation period or into 5-year (90%) accumulation period. data.benefitDescription: This rider provides for a guaranteed lifetime withdrawal benefit adjusted for the Guaranteed Growth Increase and market Step-Ups. Benefit also provides Early Access Withdrawal Option, in the Deferral Phase of the Rider and prior to the Annuity Payout Period of the contract, withdrawals may be taken that do not initiate the Withdrawal Phase of the Rider.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: On the rider effective date, withdrawal benefit base is equal to initial purchase payment. After the rider effective date, value of withdrawal benefit base is determined based on contract phase. Rider provides 2 different phases - 1) Deferral Phase; and 2) Withdrawal Phase. In the deferral phase, withdrawal benefit base can grow due to guaranteed growth increases, step-ups, or subsequent purchase payments and decrease for early access withdrawals. The period during which withdrawals are taken under the lifetime withdrawal guarantee is called the withdrawal phase. In the withdrawal phase, the withdrawal benefit base may increase with annual step-ups and decrease for excess withdrawals. At the time Lifetime Withdrawal Guarantee is exercised, the withdrawal benefit base will be set equal to the greater of - 1) contract value immediately prior to the first lifetime withdrawal, or 2) withdrawal benefit base, including the guaranteed growth increase prorated for any partial year since the prior contract anniversary. Owner may take a withdrawal during the Deferral Phase that does not initiate the Lifetime Withdrawal Guarantee and will keep the Contract in the Deferral Phase.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: The guaranteed growth increase provides an 8% simple interest increase to the withdrawal benefit base for a period of 10 years, while market step-ups lock in the market performance annually. The current Growth Rate is 8%. Guaranteed growth base is the amount used to determine the annual guaranteed growth amount and is equal to net purchase payments
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: Owner may take withdrawals annually up to the guaranteed annual withdrawal amount, which is calculated on every contract anniversary and is equal to the lifetime withdrawal rate multiplied by the withdrawal benefit base.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: A Step-Up is an increase of the Withdrawal Benefit Base to an amount equal to 100% of the Contract Value. On each Contract Anniversary until the younger Covered Life reaches the Maturity Age, Withdrawal Benefit Base will be evaluated for a Step-Up opportunity. If the Contract Value at the time of evaluation is greater than the Withdrawal Benefit Base, the Withdrawal Benefit Base will automatically Step-Up to the Contract Value. In addition, if the Contract has entered the Withdrawal Phase, the Guaranteed Annual Withdrawal Amount will increase by the same percentage as the Withdrawal Benefit Base, unless the Lifetime Withdrawal Rate is also increased.

data.feeOption: Effective annual rider charge may be increased, but will not be greater than the current charge applicable to the class of contract owners then electing the rider, and the increase may be no more than 0.50%.

On each Contract Anniversary until the younger Covered Life reaches the Maturity Age or until the Annuity Date (if earlier), Withdrawal Benefit Base will be evaluated for an Automatic Annual Step-Up opportunity. If the Contract Value at the time of evaluation is greater than the Withdrawal Benefit Base, the Withdrawal Benefit Base will automatically step-up to the Contract Value. data.notes: The withdrawal benefit base is accumulated in this way both before and after withdrawals under the living benefit guarantee are exercised. Inflation Factor is calculated based on non-seasonally adjusted Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U), published monthly by the bureau of labor statistics of the U.S. The applicable Inflation Factor is determined at the beginning of calendar month that contains the contract anniversary. Average withdrawal benefit base is used to calculate the annual inflation Increase. In the Withdrawal Phase, under the Lifetime Withdrawal Guarantee, the Inflation Increase Period will continue for as long as the contract value is greater than zero prior to age 95. Single Life Guarantee is available if annuitant is between ages 35-80; Joint Life Guarantee is available only if, annuitant is between the ages 35-85 and the younger of the annuitant and joint annuitant is between the ages 35-80; on contract date.
data.withdrawalNotes: Lifetime withdrawal rate is used to determine amount of GAWA. Lifetime withdrawal rate is the sum of age-based lifetime withdrawal rate and the effective waiting bonus if applicable. Effective waiting bonus is sum of waiting bonus for each purchase payment. For each purchase payment, the waiting bonus is ratio of- 1) which is the product of - a) age of purchase payment at time lifetime withdrawal guarantee is first exercised; b) annual adjustment rate of 0.10%; and c) purchase payment amount, and 2) total amount of purchase payments at the time lifetime withdrawal guarantee is first exercised. The age of purchase payment is defined as the greater of zero and difference between- 1) number of contract years since date of purchase payment, subject to maximum withdrawal rate adjustment period of 10 years, and 2) the withdrawal rate adjustment waiting period of 0 years.

The age of purchase payment is defined as the greater of zero and difference between- 1) number of contract years since date of purchase payment, subject to maximum withdrawal rate adjustment period of 10 years, and 2) the withdrawal rate adjustment waiting period of 0 years.

data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: Owner may take withdrawals annually up to the guaranteed annual withdrawal amount, which is calculated on every contract anniversary and is equal to the lifetime withdrawal rate multiplied by the withdrawal benefit base. Guaranteed annual withdrawal amount may increase each year when the withdrawal benefit base receives an inflation increase.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: Automatic Annual Step-Up of Withdrawal Benefit Base is an increase of the Withdrawal Benefit Base to an amount equal to 100% of the Contract Value. On each Contract Anniversary until the younger Covered Life reaches the Maturity Age or until the Annuity Date (if earlier), Withdrawal Benefit Base will be evaluated for an Automatic Annual Step-Up opportunity. If the Contract Value at the time of evaluation is greater than the Withdrawal Benefit Base, the Withdrawal Benefit Base will automatically step up to the Contract Value. In addition, if the Contract has entered the Withdrawal Phase, the Guaranteed Annual Withdrawal Amount will increase by the same percentage as the Withdrawal Benefit Base, unless you have chosen the Lifetime Withdrawal Guarantee and the Lifetime Withdrawal Rate is also increased.
data.notes: The withdrawal benefit base is accumulated in this way both before and after withdrawals under the living benefit guarantee are exercised. Inflation Factor is calculated based on non-seasonally adjusted Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U), published monthly by the bureau of labor statistics of the U.S. The applicable Inflation Factor is determined at the beginning of calendar month that contains the contract anniversary. Average withdrawal benefit base is used to calculate the annual inflation Increase. In the Withdrawal Phase, under the Lifetime Withdrawal Guarantee, the Inflation Increase Period will continue for as long as the contract value is greater than zero prior to age 95.
